<h1>B&W Swine Incident</h1>

<div class="log">
DATE: 10/14/26<br><br>

Roughtly 1000 swine pretaining to group A5 were found dead at approximately 5:30am.<br>
Analysis determined no outside threat but rather an internal one.<br>
Each swine was found with bite marks matching those of a pig.<br>
Of the 1000 swine 200 of them were found with their stomachs ruptered.<br>
Analysis of the swine's stomach reveal:<br>
Bone and teeth fragments.<br>
Muscle tissue with proteins matching those from a pig.<br>
and stomach Ulcers.<br>
Cause Unknown.<br>

</div>

<h1>Letter from CEO Ken Park</h1>

<div class="log">
DATE: 10/17/26<br><br>

How it is possible that something like this went under the rug?<br>
We ship nationwide! We shipped Swine from A5 to Miami, Mason, and Salado! <br>
And they distributed our products to stores across this country!<br>
It's only a matter of time until someone calls in sick after eating pork from our company...<br>

I've seen some of our employees laugh and dismiss our current predicament but let me be clear:<br>
We don't have a patient zero, we don't know how this disease spread, and we don't know how many of our current swine are infected.<br>
What we are facing is an unknown pathogen that we have to PRAY is not infectious to people!<br>
one pig gives us 160lb of meat thats:<br>
Ham<br>
Sausage<br>
Bacon<br>
Ribs<br>
And a lot of things that the average american, including your families, eat on a daily basis.<br>

I pray nothing happens...<br>

</div>

